review_blob: Not what I was expecting. An okay pale ale, but nothing about this really stands out for me. The hops are pungent enough. It just lacks the crisp finish Id want, not to mention the burst of flavor on the tongue or lasting hoppiness Id prefer in an IPA. The flavor is lasting, but only as bitterness.

A pretty good brown ale. Aroma is of caramel and nuts, a bit of smokiness. Earlier in the bomber when the carbonation is a little stronger this has a better mouthfeel. As this warms it loses carbonation quickly and gets a little too flat for my liking. Good mix of sweet malt and bitter finish. Id drink this again.
beer_name: Rock Art Petes Greens Barn Raising Brown

review_blob: What a phenomenal beer. Smell is of hops and citrus; taste is fairly sweet, very slightly bitter. It has a very sticky, heavy mouth-feel. Its very hard to label this an ESB... definitely a stretch on Rock Arts part. But who cares? This beer is great, whatever you want to call it--Imperial ESB or American Strong Ale.
beer_name: Rock Art Magnumus ete Tomahawkus ESB2 Ale

review_blob: Pours as black as a stout, with an off-white head. Tastes quite bitter on the finish, but the initial taste is malty and sweet. Bitterness fades in the aftertaste and leaves the sweetness behind. My recommendation for this beer is to let it warm up. This is my fifth time drinking it and youll want it out of the fridge for about an hour to fully release the flavors. Great beer from Rock Art.

Great stuff. Poured slow and still produced a massive head. Very light carbonation and mellow hop character make for a super sessionable brew. The aroma is pretty light on the nose but the minute you take a sip the flavor really blossoms. Id love to try this on tap.

Valentines present to myself and so good... Aroma is malty as hell. Toffee, liquor, oak--its all there. Taste is sweet & the lightest hint of sour. It feels light on the tongue and goes down smooth. I could drink this for weeks on end.

You can smell the smokiness right away, but the big story with this beer is taste. A substantial feeling beer, its thick maltiness is undercut with a noticeable dose of hops. As it warms up it only gets tastier. A true winter beer and one Ive underestimated in the past.
beer_name: Rock Art Stump Jumper Gnarly Stout

review_blob: Excellent bitter. It smells of caramel, tastes moderately bitter. In terms of feel on the palate it manages to be both crisp and substantial. Id drink it again for sure.

I wasnt very impressed. The flavor was so light I found myself repeatedly sipping it and pausing just to get a better idea of what I was drinking. The taste is mildly sweet, with a light kick of alcohol on top. As for aroma, it didnt strike me as much more than a mild breadiness, with the lightest hint of cherry.

I enjoyed this a lot. It has a faintly sweet aroma, almost like toffee. A light caramel color, it appears to be almost non-carbonated but you can feel the light carbonation on the tongue. Its a crisp beer that goes down easy, leaving a lasting but mild bitterness on the tongue. I could easily session this.
Smells wonderful. The taste doesnt quite match the aroma, but a very nice brew. Maybe a bit more bitter than your typical brown ale. A standby for me.

A very drinkable porter, but hardly memorable. I mean that literally, because I had this months ago  and other than thinking it was okay I could recall very little about it. It has a mild aroma of fruit (dates?) and caramel. Theres little head to speak of, even when poured quickly. The mouth-feel is smooth with very light carbonation. Again, drinkable but there are too many great porters out there for me to buy this again.
